  4. There are hints provided in Coursera, feel free to explore the hints if needed. Each hint provide progressively more details on how to solve the issue. This project is intended to be comprehensive and difficult if you do it without the hints.

The Assignment¶

Take a ZIP file) of images and process them, using a library built into python that you need to learn how to use. A ZIP file takes several different files and compresses them, thus saving space, into one single file. The files in the ZIP file we provide are newspaper images (like you saw in week 3). Your task is to write python code which allows one to search through the images looking for the occurrences of keywords and faces. E.g. if you search for "pizza" it will return a contact sheet of all of the faces which were located on the newspaper page which mentions "pizza". This will test your ability to learn a new (library), your ability to use OpenCV to detect faces, your ability to use tesseract to do optical character recognition, and your ability to use PIL to composite images together into contact sheets.

Each page of the newspapers is saved as a single PNG image in a file called images.zip. These newspapers are in english, and contain a variety of stories, advertisements and images. Note: This file is fairly large (~200 MB) and may take some time to work with, I would encourage you to use small_img.zip for testing.

Here's an example of the output expected. Using the small_img.zip file, if I search for the string "Christopher" I should see the following image: If I were to use the images.zip file and search for "Mark" I should see the following image (note that there are times when there are no faces on a page, but a word is found!):

Note: That big file can take some time to process - for me it took nearly ten minutes! Use the small one for testing.

# Alright Need to make all of this into a function that receives a keyword and zipped file folder for final project prompts with each zip

def search_face_sheet(zip_file, keyword):
    zip_images = {}
    with zipfile.ZipFile(zip_file, 'r') as zipped:
        newspapers = zipped.infolist() # alias list of zipped files from above context manager
        for newspaper in newspapers: # iterate through class 'zipfile.ZipInfo' types
        #print(type(newspaper))
            with zipped.open(newspaper) as zipextfile: # use alias outside w/context and open method to open file
            #display(Image.open(zipextfile)) # michigan daily newspaper images - images successfully display
            #print(type(nwsp, dir(newspaper), dir(zipextfile)) - filename is not in the file but how the image opens 
                img = Image.open(zipextfile).convert('RGB') # Conversion should help for facial recognition from Module 3
                zip_images[newspaper.filename] = {'PIL_img': img}
            
    # Next piece of logic
    for img in zip_images.keys():
    # pass pil_img for key name to ocr:pytesseract
        img_text = pytesseract.image_to_string(zip_images[img]['PIL_img'])
        zip_images[img]['img_text'] = img_text
    
    # Next pice of logic
    for newspaper_img in zip_images.keys():
    # convert to numpy array for PIL image for each key
        np_image_gs = np.array(zip_images[newspaper_img]['PIL_img'])
    # numpy array can now be converted to grayscale
        gscale_img = cv.cvtColor(np_image_gs, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    # use face_cascade, had more luck with a third argument passed to get fewer false positives 
        faces_bboxes = face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gscale_img, 1.3, 5)
    # So with the detected face box parameters, instead of drawing a rectangle or "box", we could crop then subsequently create a thumbnail
    # Create new 'faces' or like key for each image as an empty list (will append img then thumbnail (can't be done at same time))
        zip_images[newspaper_img]['faces'] = []
    # iterate over each 2D numpy array box values should faces_bboxes len be greater than or equal to 1 (2D numpy array return from detectMultiScale method)
        if len(faces_bboxes) >= 1:
            for x, y, w, h in faces_bboxes:
                # crop numpy bounding box values for individual face
                individual_face = zip_images[newspaper_img]['PIL_img'].crop((x, y, x+w, y+h))
                # append to new faces list created for the dictionary holding image and text value
                zip_images[newspaper_img]['faces'].append(individual_face)
                # Couldn't append a thumbnail image as the individual_face image so just resampled and changed the size after initially placing into new key for the eventual contact sheet
                for face in zip_images[newspaper_img]['faces']:
                    face.thumbnail((100, 100), Image.Resampling.LANCZOS)
    
    # Next piece of logic
    for nwsp_zip_file in zip_images.keys():
        # see if 'keyword' in img_text key
        if keyword in zip_images[nwsp_zip_file]['img_text']:
            # check if key's faces list is empty
            if len(zip_images[nwsp_zip_file]['faces']) == 0:
                # print statement that keyword found but no faces over two lines
                print("Results found in file {} \nBut there were no faces in that file!".format(nwsp_zip_file))
            else:
                # keyword and faces, create a contact sheet
                print(f"Results found in file {nwsp_zip_file}")
                # Set number of rows for new Image (ContactSheet)
                height = math.ceil(len(zip_images[nwsp_zip_file]['faces'])/5)
                # New Contact sheet (defaults to black similar to first module project when changing rows)
                csheet = Image.new('RGB', (500, 100 * height))
                # set x, y default values for image pasting
                x, y = 0, 0
                for thumbnail_img in zip_images[nwsp_zip_file]['faces']:
                    csheet.paste(thumbnail_img, (x, y))
                    if x + 100 == csheet.width:
                        x = 0
                        y += 100
                    else:
                        x += 100
                display(csheet)
    return
